<DOC id="CNA_ENG_19970925.0027" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
M2 MONEY SUPPLY GROWTH AT NEW LOW
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  Sept.  25  (CNA)
(By Bear Lee)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The M2 money supply growth plunged to a
new low of 7.09 percent in August, according to the Central Bank of
China (CBC).
</P>
<P>
CBC attributed the low growth -- a five-consecutive-month decline
-- to a booming stock market and a slowdown in bank loans and
investment, as well as an increase in government deposits.
</P>
<P>
The M2 is the broadest measure of a country's money stocks. It
comprises currency in circulation, checking accounts, demand deposits
and quasi money (including time deposits and treasury bills).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the more-narrowly defined M1A money supply, which
includes cash, checking accounts and demand deposits, grew by 10.84
percent in the same month, the highest level since November 1994, the
CBC said.
</P>
<P>
The M1B, which comprises the M1A plus passbook savings deposits,
also hit a 33-month high of 17.06 percent, it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
