</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Ankara,  Sept.  27 (CNA)
(By Kuo Chuan-hsing)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Turkey led Western Europe During 1993-95
in arms import expenditure, according to a new report entitled "World
Military Expenditures and Arms Transfers 1996" released by the US
Arms Control and Disarmament Agency (ACDA).
</P>
<P>
A Turkish defense magazine quoted ACDA as saying that Turkey,
which spent US$3 billion on arms during 1993-95, is followed by
Greece (US$2.2 billion), Spain (US$1.6 billion) and Germany (US$1.3
billion).
</P>
<P>
The United States, as expected, was the number one supplier of
arms to Turkey and others in Europe, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, according to ACDA, has the world's sixth-largest army,
with 805,000 troops, behind mainland China (2.93 million), the United
States (1.62 million), Russia (1.40 million), India (1.26 million)
and North Korea (1.04 million)
