<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN PC PRODUCTION EXPECTED TO REACH 10 MILLION THIS YEAR
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  Sept.  30  (CNA)
(By Elizabeth Hsu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With the increasing development of the
computer hardware industry, Taiwan's annual production of personal
computers (PCs) is expected to break the 10 million unit mark at the
end of this year, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The statistics, released recently by the Directorate General of
Budget, Accounting and Statistics (DGBAS), show that Taiwan produced
5.8 million PCs during the first six months of this year,
representing a 45.3 percent rise in comparison with the same period
of last year.
</P>
<P>
The DGBAS statistics also show that the accumulated value of this
production reached US$5.4 billion in the six-month period, up 58.6
percent from the year-earlier level.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's computer industry has been enjoying exciting growth in
PC production, including desktop and notebook PCs, over the past five
years, with total PC production surging to 9.46 million units in 1996
from 2.8 million in 1992, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The figures represent an average 36.2 percent annual growth for
PC production on the island, the DGBAS indicated.
</P>
<P>
In terms of total production value, the DGBAS figures indicate a
jump to US$8.7 billion in 1996 from 1992's US$2.1 billion, with an
annual growth average of 42.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the statistics also show that although desktop PCs
enjoyed a larger annual output than notebook PCs over the past five
years, the latter had an average 44.7 percent growth per annum,
higher the former's 31.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The DGBAS said, however, that most of this production was in the
form of original equipment manufacturer (OEM), accounting for 69
percent of the entire output during the Jan.-June period of this
year, reflecting the fact that Taiwan computer makers still need to
make more efforts in R&amp;D for their own products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
