<DATELINE>
Taipei,  Sept.  30  (CNA)
(By Debbie Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MOFA)
said on Tuesday that Taipei welcomes the United States' positive
attitude toward the signing of an extradition treaty with Taiwan,
even though the MOFA has not yet been officially notified by the US
government in this regard.
</P>
<P>
MOFA spokesman Roy Wu said the ROC welcomes the signing of such
an agreement since the two countries have maintained close
cooperative relations in crime-busting efforts, but lack the laws to
govern these efforts.
</P>
<P>
Wu said Taipei has on many occasions discussed with relevant US
officials the signing of an extradition accord so that the two sides
can join forces to curb cross-border crimes, but added that no
decisive progress has been made so far.
</P>
<P>
The MOFA is hoping for an extradition agreement to cover
criminals involved in drug trafficking, arms smuggling and organized
crime, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
According to wire service reports, the US is preparing to sign an
extradition treaty with Taiwan. "Discussions on this matter have been
going on for some time, but it's not something upon which we could
reach consensus immediately," said Lloyd Neighbors, spokesman for the
American Institute in Taiwan (AIT), the de facto Washington embassy
in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on developments in a cross-border drug trafficking
case concerning ROC national Huang Kuang-chieh, Wu said the case has
entered the judicial process and the ROC will take care of it.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the ROC's stance on a US demand that Huang be
repatriated from Taiwan to America to face trial, Wu said the ROC
government has turned down the request on the grounds that the two
countries maintain no extradition treaty.
