In a statement issued after returning his party membership
certificate to local KMT headquarters, Chang said he is resigning
because that will make it easier for him to convince his supporters
that he will not be dropped from the race at a later date because of
KMT pressure, which will make it easier for him to solicit votes.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the KMT for not putting him on the party ticket
despite his staunch efforts to canvass party support during numerous
previous elections.
</P>
<P>
Chang's resignation signifies the failure of the KMT to reconcile
three party hopefuls for the county magistrate race in Yunlin after
the party chose provincial assemblyman Su Wen-hsiung as its
candidate.
</P>
<P>
Su told reporters after learning of Chang's resignation that it
represents a boost for his candidacy because it avoids any question
of a party split.
</P>
<P>
Another KMT hopeful, Ou Ming-hsian, said that same day that he
will not quit the party but will instead seek its approval to allow
him to stand as a candidate in parallel with Su.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
